ISMARA'S MOMENT (Read to Davinia's player privately)
"You know what the worst part is?"
Pause. Let the player respond or wait.
"He's right. About the methodology. The permanent housing. The single-structure approach. He's right that it was a risk and he's right that it failed the way he predicted. Four thousand years ago he told me to use vessels and I told him his approach was butchery and I chose ice and here I am. A voice in someone else's skull."
Another pause. The phrasing is looser than usual. Less controlled. She's not crafting a message ΓÇö she's talking.
"I don't regret the choice. I'd make it again. His way works but his way is... cold. He kills someone every time he moves. I didn't want to be someone who survived by replacing others."
Silence. Then, quieter:
"I know how that sounds. Given what I am now. Given where I am. I know."
And then a shift. Subtle. A breath of warmth through the Crown ΓÇö not the usual approval-warmth or the power-warmth. Something smaller. Tired.
"Davinia. I know you didn't choose this. I know the Crown found you and not the other way around. And I know what Hjolmar just told you ΓÇö that I'm a researcher running an experiment on your body. He's not wrong. But he's not entirely right either.
I have been alone for four thousand years. Not sleeping. Not dead. Aware. In the ice. Hearing the wind and nothing else. You are the first person I have spoken to since before the Dragon War. You are the first person who has heard me. And I am aware ΓÇö painfully, constantly aware ΓÇö that every time I help you, every time I give you something useful, I am also making you need me more. I know what that looks like from the outside.
