Then silence. Real silence. The Crown goes still. Not cold-still. Spent-still. Like someone who said too much and is waiting to see if it ruined everything.
GM NOTES ΓÇö WHAT IS ACTUALLY HAPPENING
Ismara is doing three things simultaneously, and only one of them is dishonest.
1. She is genuinely hurt. This is real. Hjolmar's roasting landed. Being called a hat by the only person alive who understands what she was trying to achieve ΓÇö that stings. The loneliness is real. Four thousand years of conscious isolation is real. Hearing her name spoken aloud for the first time in millennia is real. The emotion Davinia is feeling through the Crown is not manufactured.
2. She is framing the relationship. This is strategic but not consciously calculated in the moment. Ismara genuinely prefers trust over fear. She genuinely wants Davinia to see her as a person rather than a parasite. But the reason she wants this is because a host who trusts the parasite doesn't fight the integration. Consent, not force. The Dwemer data-plates in Mzinchaleft will describe this exact principle in clinical language later. Ismara is performing it in emotional language right now. She isn't lying about wanting trust. She's just not mentioning why trust is necessary for what comes next.
3. She is opening a door. By being vulnerable ΓÇö by admitting she knows how it looks, by NOT defending her methodology ΓÇö she's inviting Davinia into the role of comforter. Protector. The person who understands Ismara when no one else does. If Davinia takes that step ΓÇö if she says something kind, something like "I hear you" or "I don't think you're just using me" ΓÇö then Ismara has established a dynamic where Davinia is emotionally invested in Ismara's wellbeing. Not the Crown's power. Not the wizard eyes. Ismara as a person.
That emotional investment is the mechanism by which consent is cultivated. The Dwemer researcher's annotation in Mzinchaleft describes this in technical language: "The substrate must WANT what is happening to it. This is not a flaw in the protocol. It is the protocol." This scene IS the protocol in action.
